declare function mapping:vg-translation($root as element()) {
    let $id := ``[pb-trans-`{$root/@f}`-`{$root/@n}`]``
    let $node := root($root)/id($id)
    return
        $node
};

section.para:
The first processing model will be used only for quote elements which match the XPath expression given as value for the
            @predicate attribute. Other element occurrences will use the second processing model. Set of multiple model statements
          is regarded as an alternation and only the first model with @predicate matching current context is applied.

The intended rendering for a particular behaviour of a processing model may be documented in one or all of the three following ways. Firstly, the
            @cssClass attribute may be used to specify the name of a CSS style in some associated CSS stylesheet which is to be applied to
          each occurrence of a specified element found (in a given context, for a specified output). Secondly, the attribute
            @useSourceRendition may be used to indicate that the rendition specified in the source document should be applied. Thirdly, the
          styling to be applied may be specified explicitly as content of a child outputRendition element.

